You can achieve this by modifying the JavaScript code to display the alt text of the image when the user hovers over it. Here is how you can do it:

```javascript
const stationInfo = [
    '<img src="https://cdn.glitch.global/f4cb3da3-e38f-4c57-8538-cd16160b85b3/539561ldsdl.jpg?v=1710171387673" class="center" alt="The Admiral House, Simon’s Town, Cape of Good Hope" width="400"> The Admiral House, Simon’s Town, Cape of Good Hope (1844) by Lt. Humphrey John Julian <br><br> From the <a href=\'https://collections.britishart.yale.edu/catalog/tms:10760\'>Yale Center for British Art</a>.</p>',
    'This text is in <p></p> but it will not display on hover'
];

const hoverText = document.getElementById('hoverText');

hoverText.innerHTML = stationInfo[0]; // Display the image and text on page load

hoverText.addEventListener('mouseover', function() {
    const image = hoverText.querySelector('img'); // Find the img element within the hoverText div
    hoverText.innerHTML = image.alt; // Display the alt text of the image when user hovers over it
});

hoverText.addEventListener('mouseout', function() {
    hoverText.innerHTML = stationInfo[0]; // Return to displaying the image and initial text when user moves mouse away
});
```

In this modified code, we first set the content of the `hoverText` div to display the image and text when the page loads. Then, when the user hovers over the image, we find the image element within the `hoverText` div and display its alt text. When the user moves the mouse away, we revert back to displaying the original image and text.

Make sure to adjust the HTML or CSS code accordingly to fit your specific layout and design requirements.

